<span id="freeTextContainer2464286410357380536">The most famous narrative of D-Day that was published within a decade or so after the war. There are more comprehensive books out there today for sure. <br/><br/>The negative — Not terribly heavy with facts and detail such as no maps. Very little coverage of the Allied pre-planning. <br/><br/>The positive. A unique view of both sides. There was equal coverage and interviews with German soldiers mixed in with the Allies. An excellent job of detailing what the German commanders and soldiers were thinking during the i</span>
  <span id="freeText2464286410357380536" style="display:none">The most famous narrative of D-Day that was published within a decade or so after the war. There are more comprehensive books out there today for sure. <br /><br />The negative — Not terribly heavy with facts and detail such as no maps. Very little coverage of the Allied pre-planning. <br /><br />The positive. A unique view of both sides. There was equal coverage and interviews with German soldiers mixed in with the Allies. An excellent job of detailing what the German commanders and soldiers were thinking during the invasion, including many pages on a missing and remorseful Rommel who decided to take some leave back to Germany. <br /><br />4 stars. </span>
