    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4361283779" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4361283779" />
    <a title="C.H. Cobb" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5767233-c-h-cobb"><img alt="C.H. Cobb" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1597615488p2/5767233.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4361283779?book_show_action=true">Nov 28, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="C.H. Cobb" class="user" itemprop="url" name="C.H. Cobb" href="/user/show/5767233-c-h-cobb">C.H. Cobb</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780671890919" href="/book/show/49467907-the-longest-day">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4361283779" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9995492541571377547">This is an outstanding history of an epic event covering primarily a 24-hour period. Ryan&apos;s account of the Normandy invasion was considered to be one of the best of his era. Though the work was published in 1959, it remains one of the principal accounts of D-Day to this day. Part one of the book covers the runup to D-Day, which is important for establish context as well as the agonizing on-again, off-again actions of June 4th. Part two explores actions on the night of June 5th and early morning </span>
  <span id="freeText9995492541571377547" style="display:none">This is an outstanding history of an epic event covering primarily a 24-hour period. Ryan's account of the Normandy invasion was considered to be one of the best of his era. Though the work was published in 1959, it remains one of the principal accounts of D-Day to this day. Part one of the book covers the runup to D-Day, which is important for establish context as well as the agonizing on-again, off-again actions of June 4th. Part two explores actions on the night of June 5th and early morning of the 6th. Part three begins at dawn of June 6th.<br /><br />Employing extensive interviews with the actual participants and unit histories from both the Allies and Axis, Ryan pieces together accounts of individual soldiers and officers so intimate that the reader can practically hear the gunfire and feel the fear.<br /><br />The writing style is superb and the content even better. No student of D-Day can afford to miss this book. This is now my third read-through in probably 30 years, and I enjoyed it as much, if not more, than my first time. Five stars, highly recommended.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9995492541571377547" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


